        <h2>Your journey into the world of Cybersecurity starts here!</h2>
        <h3>About Cybersecurity</h3>
        <p>Cybersecurity involves protecting computer systems, networks, and data from digital attacks. It plays a crucial role in safeguarding sensitive information and ensuring the integrity of digital infrastructure.</p>
        <p>In this section, we will explore the fundamentals of cybersecurity, its importance in business, and the various career paths available in this field.</p>
        <p>Whether you are considering a career in cybersecurity or simply want to understand its principles, this guide will provide you with the necessary insights.</p>
        <p>Cybersecurity in business involves implementing measures to protect against cyber threats and ensure the security of digital assets.</p>

        <h3>What is Cybersecurity?</h3>
        <p>Cybersecurity is the practice of defending computers, servers, mobile devices, electronic systems, networks, and data from malicious attacks. It includes activities such as threat detection, risk management, and incident response.</p>
        <p>Understanding cybersecurity is crucial for anyone looking to pursue a career in IT, security, or management. It helps in making informed decisions, managing resources effectively, and ensuring the protection of digital assets.</p>
        
        <h3>Key Responsibilities</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Threat Detection:</b> Identifying potential cyber threats and vulnerabilities</li>
            <li><b>Risk Management:</b> Assessing and mitigating risks to protect digital assets</li>
            <li><b>Incident Response:</b> Responding to and managing security breaches and incidents</li>
            <li><b>Security Policy Development:</b> Creating and implementing security policies and procedures</li>
            <li><b>Network Security:</b> Protecting network infrastructure from unauthorized access and attacks</li>
            <li><b>Data Protection:</b> Ensuring the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data</li>
        </ul>

